issue.title: [Feature]: Add `getText()` method on ElementHandle
issue.body:
### Feature description

# Shorter interface for getting text of an element

## Why ?
For people using puppeteer for web scraping, it is really common to get the `innerText` of elements.

How common ? [This question](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55237748/how-to-get-text-inside-div-in-puppeteer) on StackOverflow has gathered 121'000 views, 54+ upvotes, and 8 answers (with plenty of upvotes also).

And there [are](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/68158601/using-puppeteer-to-extract-text-from-span) [multiple](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66173666/how-to-get-html-element-text-using-puppeteer) [such](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/71639420/puppeteer-how-to-extract-content-from-a-page-that-have-multiple-divs-with-same) [questions]()

## Symptoms

So our code is filled with :

```js
const theElement = page.waitForSelector(sel);
const theText = theElement.$eval(el => el.innerText)
```

This two-liner seems redundant. I also have this a lot:

```js
let studData = {
            name:       await student.$eval('td:nth-of-type(1)', el => el.innerText),
            department: await student.$eval('td:nth-of-type(2)', el => el.innerText),
            date:       await student.$eval(`td:nth-of-type(4)`, el => el.innerText),
}
```

## Current workaround

None yielded from my search.

I tried to extend `ElementHandle` or `JSHandle`, but it doesn't work:

```js
    // extend Element to be able to get text directly
    puppeteer.ElementHandle.prototype.getText = async function(selector) {
        return this.$eval(selector, el => el.innerText);
      };
```
I'm not a typescript guy, but I believe [this answers](https://stackoverflow.com/a/66327189/786559) why this cannot work. 

## Desired feature

Wouldn't it be a lot more elegant if we had `ElementHandle.getText(selector)` ? 

```js
let studData = {
            name:       await student.getText('td:nth-of-type(1)'),
            department: await student.getText('td:nth-of-type(2)'),
            date:       await student.getText(`td:nth-of-type(4)`),
}
```

Or it could be called `student.$text()`. The `$` still indicates we'll take a selector as first argument.

## Alternative 

Maybe even a custom QuerySelector that doesn't just search for text, but actually returns it . (although this is not such a good solution because it woudl return string so it breaks the interface of returning a `HandleFor`)

---

Any of these interfaces would save a lot of intermediate steps.

---

issue.title: [Bug]: Puppeteer 21 not communicating with cromium on arm64

comment.body:
Oh, sorry, I've made a mistake. I got it running with `google-chrome-stable` but on amd64 not on **arm64**.

So I tried what was recommended by @OrKoN 

> I am unable to reproduce locally. Please see https://pptr.dev/troubleshooting#running-puppeteer-in-docker as the issue is probably related to the docker image. Consider trying the following: 1) checking that all dependencies are installed https://pptr.dev/troubleshooting#chrome-doesnt-launch-on-linux 2) configure the sandbox 3) make sure dbus is started and has a proper DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS in the env vars.

I installed everything i found in available dockerfiles. I configured sandbox (`args: ["--no-sandbox", "--disable-setuid-sandbox"],`) and I checked dbus and it wasn't started but even if I start it, there's no change.

The issue is, that chromium gets started, I can see it in `ps -aux` output.

I understand that, you are not supporting chromium, but what are we supposed to do on arm? Thanks.
